ces==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{US Country Albums}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of number-one country albums in the United States|2016]]\n[[Category:2016 record charts|United States Country Albums]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Fourth_of_July_in_Guantanamo_DVIDS297046.jpg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Singers Joey + Rory|''[[Hymns That Are Important to Us]]'' by [[Joey + Rory]] reached number one in the issue of ''Billboard'' dated March 5, 2016.  [[Joey Feek]] (left) died on March 4.]]\n[[Top Country Albums]] is a [[record chart|chart]] that ranks the top-performing [[country music]] albums in the United States, published by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.  In 2016, 22 different albums topped the chart; placings were based on electronic [[point of sale]] data from retail outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7669133/billboard-genre-album-charts-consumption-streams-track-sales|title=Billboard's Genre Album Charts Will Now Incorporate Streams & Track Sales|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{-}}\n==Chart history==\n[[File:Sturgill_Simpson_photo_2016_(cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Sturgill Simpson|[[Sturgill Simpson]] topped the chart for the first time with ''[[A Sailor's Guide to Earth]]''.]]\n[[File:Steven Tyler by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Steven Tyler|[[Steven Tyler]], lead singer of the rock band [[Aerosmith]], reached number one with his solo album ''[[We're All Somebody from Somewhere]]''.]]\n[[File:Chris_Stapleton_May_23,_2017.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Chris Stapleton|[[Chris Stapleton] spent the most weeks at number one in 2016.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=col|Issue date\n!scope=col|Title\n!scope=col|Artist(s)\n\n!scope=col class=unsortable|Ref.\n|-\n| January 2\n| rowspan=\"9\"| ''[[Traveller (Chris Stapleton album)|Traveller]]''\n| rowspan=\"9\"| [[Chris Stapleton]]\n\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=ht