9-15}}</ref>\n|}\n{{Top of page}}\n\n==Traveling teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#a8bdec; width:26%;\"| Team !! style=\"width:7%; background:#a8bdec;\"| 1st Yr !! style=\"width:7%; background:#a8bdec;\"| Last Yr !! style=\"width:16%; background:#a8bdec;\"| Affiliation(s) !! style=\"width:40%; background:#a8bdec;\"| Notes !! style=\"width:4%; background:#a8bdec;\"| Ref\n|- \n| [[All Cubans]] || 1899 || 1905 || Independent ||\n*Precursor of '''Cuban Stars (West)'''\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- \n| [[All Nations]] || 1912 || 1925 || Independent ||\n*Based out of '''Kansas City MO''' and '''Des Moines IA'''\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- \n| [[Chappie Johnson's Stars]] ||  ||  ||  || \n*Led by [[Chappie Johnson|George \"Chappie\" Johnson]]\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- \n| [[House of David (commune)|Colored House of David]] ||  ||  ||  ||  || {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- style=\"background:#ffffe0;\" \n| <u>'''[[Cuban Stars (East)]] club'''</u>\n*'''New York Cuban Stars''' (1916\u201319)\n*'''Havana Cuban Stars''' (1920)\n*'''Cuban Stars (East)''' (1921\u2013{{circa|lk=no|34}})\n|| 1916 || {{circa|1934}} || Independent (1916\u201322)<br>[[Eastern Colored League|ECL]] (1923\u201328)<br>[[American Negro League|ANL]] (1929)<br>Independent (1930\u2013{{circa|lk=no|34}}) ||\n*Played road games primarily in the New York and northeast region of the US\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- id=\"Cuban Stars (West)\" style=\"background:#ffffe0;\" \n| <u>'''[[Cuban Stars (West)]] club'''</u>\n*'''Cuban Stars of Havana''' (1906\u201319)\n*'''Cincinnati Cuban Stars''' (1920\u201321)\n*'''Cuban Stars (West)''' (1922\u201332)\n|| 1906 || 1932 || [[International League of Independent Professional Base Ball Clubs|IL]] (1906)<br>[[National Association of Colored Baseball Clubs of the United States and Cuba|NA]] (1907\u201309)<br>Independent (1910\u201319)<br>[[Negro National League (1920\u201331)|NNL1]] (1920\u201330)<br>Independent (1931)<br>[[East-West League|EWL]] (1932) ||\n*Played road games for its first five years primarily in the eastern states near New York City and Philadelphia\n*By 1916 the team was competing primarily in the northern midwestern states\n*Based in '''Cincinnati''' 1920\u201321 and then returned to playing only road games\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- \n| Ethiopian Clowns<br><small>(See '''[[#Indianapolis Clowns|Indianapolis Clowns]]''')</small> || {{circa|1930s}} || 1942 || Independent ({{circa|lk=no|1930s}}\u201342) ||\n*Generally based out of '''Miami'''\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- \n| [[Mineola Black Spiders]] || {{circa|1932}} || {{circa|lk=no|1937}} || Independent ||\n*Generally based out of northern '''Iowa'''\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|- \n| [[New York Gorhams]] || 1886 || 1892 || Independent (1886)<br>[[National Colored Base Ball League|NCBBL]] (1887)<br>Independent (1888\u201392) ||\n*Generally based out of various East coast cites from New Jersey to Connecticut\n|| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/nlb/team.cgi?id=4c9066db|title=1887 New York Gorhams|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2013-10-09}}</ref>\n|- \n| [[Secret Nine]] || 1931 || 1931 || Independent || \n*Based out of '''New Orleans'''\n*Sponsored by [[Louis Armstrong]]\n|| <ref name=\"Diamonds in the Rough\">{{cite web|url=http://www.myneworleans.com/Louisiana-Life/May-June-2012/Diamonds-in-the-Rough/|title=Diamonds in the Rough|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>\n|- \n| [[Tennessee Rats]] || {{circa|1911}} || {{circa|lk=no|1926}} || Independent ||\n*Generally not considered a Negro league team\n*Based out of '''Holden MO'''\n|| {{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n|}\n{{Top of page}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nlbm.com/s/team.htm Leagues & Teams] at the [[Negro Leagues Baseball Museum]]\n* [http://www.nlbpa.com/the-negro-league-teams The Negro League Teams] at the Negro League Baseball Players Association\n* [http://www.seamheads.com/NegroLgs/history.php?tab=8a Negro Leagues Database] at Seamheads.com\n* [https://www.baseball-reference.com/nlb/team.cgi Negro League Team Encyclopedia] at [[Baseball-Reference.com]]\n\n{{Negro League teams|state=uncollapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball in the United States lists|Negro league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Negro league baseball]]\n[[Category:Negro league baseball teams| ]]\n", "name_user": "Bison X", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTennessee:fix fmt.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Negro_league_baseball_teams"}
{"title_page": "Urhannagh", "text_new": "'''Urhannagh''' ({{Irish derived place name|Uar\u00e1nach, meaning 'Abounding in wells or cold springs'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nUrhannagh is bounded on the north by [[Clontycarnaghan]]  townland, on the west by [[Munlough North]] townland, on the east by [[Bofealan]] townland and on the south by [[Cavanaquill]] and [[Killynaff]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are a small stream and cow pastures. Urhannagh is traversed by rural lanes. The townland covers 68 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Doorawnagh''.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf National Archives Dublin]</ref><ref>[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html]</ref> A 1630 Inquisition spells it ''Dowerhannagh''. The 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Urgawnagh''. The 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Unshonagh''.<ref>[http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan]</ref>\n\nWalter Talbot of [[Ballyconnell]] died on 26 June 1625 and his son James Talbot succeeded to the Ballyconnell estate aged just 10 years. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 20 September 1630 found that James Talbot was seized of one poll of ''Dowerhannagh'', along with other lands.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PA11-IA1&dq=Derrogeny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52JidpKzfAhVCyaQKHb4_BlgQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=Derrogeny&f=true]</ref> In 1635 James Talbot married Helen Calvert, the daughter of [[George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore]] of Maryland, USA. In the Cromwellian [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652]], James Talbot's estate was confiscated because he was a Catholic and he was granted an estate in 1655 at Castle Rubey, County Roscommon instead. He died in 1687. Talbot's land in Urhannagh was distributed as follows-\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor as being ''Lieutenant John Blackforde'', who also appears as proprietor of several other Templeport townlands in the same survey. John Blachford was born in 1598 in Ashmore, Dorset, England, the son of Richard and Frances Blachford. He became a merchant in Dorchester, Dorset but fled to France in 1633 when facing a warrant from the Exchequer for not paying customs. He married Mary Renald from Devon and died at [[Lissanover]], County Cavan in 1661 and was buried at St. Orvins in Dublin despite wishing to be buried back in Dorchester. His will was published on 9 January 1665 leaving his son John Blachford as his sole heir. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 21 May 1667 found that his widow Mary Blachford and his heir John were seized of, inter alia, the land of ''Urhunaght alias Unshonagh alias Doorhawnaght''. He had sons John, Thomas, Ambrose and William (who became a Major) and daughters Mary and Frances. Major William Blachford was born in 1658 and died at Lissanover on 28 March 1727. The Blachford family gravestones in Templeport Church read as follows- ''This monument was erected by MAJOR WILLIAM / BLASHFORD of Lisnover in 1721 to the memory of / his father, JOHN BLASHFORD, late of the same Esqr. but / from Dorchester in Dorsetshire, the place of his / nativity, who in his lifetime chose this for a burying / place, for himself and family, but died in Dublin / was buried in St. Orvins Church but his wife, MARY / RENALD of a Devonsheire family is buried here / as also three sons and two daughters, viz JOHN / AMBROSE AND THOMAS; MARY AND FRANCES / Here likewise lies buried two wives of MAJOR WILLIAM BLASHFORD, son to the said JOHN BLASHFORD viz / MARY MAGHEE of an ancient Family in Lincolnsheire. CORNET CHIDLEY BLACHFORD, son to MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD, leys buried here who dyed August ye 29th, 1722. This aboue MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD. / That erected this monument, died the 28th of March 1727, aged 69 years.''\n\nA deed dated 10 May 1744 spells the name as ''Urenagh''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=78971]</ref>\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list four tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Uranagh&search=Search],  in the ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Urhannagh Valuation Office Field books are available for December 1839.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00398.pdf]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists three landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=192157&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EUrhannagh%3C/b%3E]</ref>\n\n==Census==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Males\n! Females\n! Total Houses\n! Uninhabited\n|-\n| 1841 || 22 || 12 || 10 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 1851 || 19 || 14 || 5 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 1861 || 12 || 8 || 4 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 1871 || 9 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 1881 || 11 || 5 || 6 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 1891 || 11 || 4 || 7 || 2 || 0\n\n|}\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are three families listed in the townland,<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Lisanover/Uranagh/ ''Census of Ireland 1901'']</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are two listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Lissanover/Urhannagh/ ''Census of Ireland 1911'']</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThere seem to be no sites of historical interest in the townland.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.1096|-7.6285|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "text_old": "'''Urhannagh''' ({{Irish derived place name|Uar\u00e1nach, meaning 'Abounding in wells or cold springs'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nUrhannagh is bounded on the north by [[Clontycarnaghan]]  townland, on the west by [[Munlough North]] townland, on the east by [[Bofealan]] townland and on the south by [[Cavanaquill]] and [[Killynaff]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are a small stream and cow pastures. Urhannagh is traversed by rural lanes. The townland covers 68 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Doorawnagh''. A 1630 Inquisition spells it ''Dowerhannagh''. The 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Urgawnagh''. The 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Unshonagh''.\n\nWalter Talbot of [[Ballyconnell]] died on 26 June 1625 and his son James Talbot succeeded to the Ballyconnell estate aged just 10 years. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 20 September 1630 found that James Talbot was seized of one poll of ''Dowerhannagh'', along with other lands.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PA11-IA1&dq=Derrogeny&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52JidpKzfAhVCyaQKHb4_BlgQ6AEIMzAC#v=onepage&q=Derrogeny&f=true]</ref> In 1635 James Talbot married Helen Calvert, the daughter of [[George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore]] of Maryland, USA. In the Cromwellian [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652]], James Talbot's estate was confiscated because he was a Catholic and he was granted an estate in 1655 at Castle Rubey, County Roscommon instead. He died in 1687. Talbot's land in Urhannagh was distributed as follows-\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor as being ''Lieutenant John Blackforde'', who also appears as proprietor of several other Templeport townlands in the same survey. John Blachford was born in 1598 in Ashmore, Dorset, England, the son of Richard and Frances Blachford. He became a merchant in Dorchester, Dorset but fled to France in 1633 when facing a warrant from the Exchequer for not paying customs. He married Mary Renald from Devon and died at [[Lissanover]], County Cavan in 1661 and was buried at St. Orvins in Dublin despite wishing to be buried back in Dorchester. His will was published on 9 January 1665 leaving his son John Blachford as his sole heir. An Inquisition held in Cavan on 21 May 1667 found that his widow Mary Blachford and his heir John were seized of, inter alia, the land of ''Urhunaght alias Unshonagh alias Doorhawnaght''. He had sons John, Thomas, Ambrose and William (who became a Major) and daughters Mary and Frances. Major William Blachford was born in 1658 and died at Lissanover on 28 March 1727. The Blachford family gravestones in Templeport Church read as follows- ''This monument was erected by MAJOR WILLIAM / BLASHFORD of Lisnover in 1721 to the memory of / his father, JOHN BLASHFORD, late of the same Esqr. but / from Dorchester in Dorsetshire, the place of his / nativity, who in his lifetime chose this for a burying / place, for himself and family, but died in Dublin / was buried in St. Orvins Church but his wife, MARY / RENALD of a Devonsheire family is buried here / as also three sons and two daughters, viz JOHN / AMBROSE AND THOMAS; MARY AND FRANCES / Here likewise lies buried two wives of MAJOR WILLIAM BLASHFORD, son to the said JOHN BLASHFORD viz / MARY MAGHEE of an ancient Family in Lincolnsheire. CORNET CHIDLEY BLACHFORD, son to MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD, leys buried here who dyed August ye 29th, 1722. This aboue MAJOR WILLIAM BLACHFORD. / That erected this monument, died the 28th of March 1727, aged 69 years.''\n\nA deed dated 10 May 1744 spells the name as ''Urenagh''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=78971]</ref>\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list four tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Uranagh&search=Search],  in the ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nThe Urhannagh Valuation Office Field books are available for December 1839.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00398.pdf]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists three landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=192157&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EUrhannagh%3C/b%3E]</ref>\n\n==Census==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n! Males\n! Females\n! Total Houses\n! Uninhabited\n|-\n| 1841 || 22 || 12 || 10 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 1851 || 19 || 14 || 5 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 1861 || 12 || 8 || 4 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 1871 || 9 || 5 || 4 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 1881 || 11 || 5 || 6 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 1891 || 11 || 4 || 7 || 2 || 0\n\n|}\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are three families listed in the townland,<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Lisanover/Uranagh/ ''Census of Ireland 1901'']</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are two listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Lissanover/Urhannagh/ ''Census of Ireland 1911'']</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThere seem to be no sites of historical interest in the townland.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.1096|-7.6285|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "name_user": "Cormac1cormac1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urhannagh"}
{"title_page": "Glen Affric", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Glen Affric National Nature Reserve\n| alt_name = \n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Islands - panoramio (2).jpg\n| photo_alt = Pinewoods at Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin\n| photo_caption = Pinewoods at Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin\n| photo_width = \n| map = Scotland Highland\n| relief = 1\n| map_alt = Location within the Highland council area\n| map_caption = Location within the Highland council area\n| map_width = \n| location = [[Cannich]], [[Highland (council area)|Highland]], Scotland\n| coordinates = {{coord|57.23596|N|5.15327|W|region:GB_source:placeopedia|display=inline, title}}\n| area_km2 = 145\n| area_ref =<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=8169|title=Site Details for Glen Affric|accessdate=28 March 2018|date=5 March 2018|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage}}</ref>\n| established = 2002<ref name=scene>{{cite web|url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/nature-and-culture/setting-the-scene/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Setting the Scene|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=13 July 2016 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref>\n| designation = [[Scottish Natural Heritage]]\n| operator = [[Forestry and Land Scotland]]\n| url = [http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/visit/glen-affric Glen Affric National Nature Reserve]\n| embedded = \n}}\n'''Glen Affric''' ({{lang-gd|Gleann Afraig}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ainmean-aite.scot/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Forestry.pdf|publisher=Ainmean-\u00c0ite na h-Alba|accessdate=1 March 2019|date=2013|title=Forestry Commission 2013}}</ref> is a [[glen]] south-west of the village of [[Cannich]] in the [[Highland (council area)|Highland]] region of [[Scotland]], some {{convert|15|mi|km}} to the west of [[Loch Ness]]. The River Affric runs along its length, passing through [[Loch Affric]] and Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin. A minor public road reaches as far as the end of Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin, but beyond that point only rough tracks and footpaths continue along the glen.<ref name=sheet25>[[Ordnance Survey]] 1:50000 Landranger Sheet 25, ''Glen Carron and Glen Affric.''</ref>\n\nOften described as the most beautiful [[glen]] in Scotland, Glen Affric contains the third largest area of ancient [[Caledonian Forest|Caledonian pinewoods]] in Scotland, as well as [[loch]]s, [[moorland]] and mountains.<ref name=qualities>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.scot/sites/default/files/2017-07/Publication%202010%20-%20SNH%20Commissioned%20Report%20374%20-%20The%20Special%20Qualities%20of%20the%20National%20Scenic%20Areas.pdf|title=The special qualities of the National Scenic Areas|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=2010|accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\nThe area is a [[Caledonian Forest]] Reserve,<ref name=pinewood>{{cite web|url=https://data.gov.uk/dataset/caledonian-pinewood-inventory|title=Caledonian Pinewood Inventory|publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> a [[National scenic area (Scotland)|national scenic area]] and a [[National nature reserve (Scotland)|national nature reserve]], as well as holding several other [[protected areas of Scotland|conservation designations]].<ref name = sitelink>{{cite web| url=http://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/searchmap.jsp |title=Sitelink \u2013 Map Search |publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe forests and open landscapes of the glen, and the mountains on either side, are a popular destination for hikers, climbers and mountain bikers.<ref name=\"HumphreysReid2012\">{{cite book|first1=Rob |last1=Humphreys|first2=Donald |last2=Reid|title=The Great Glen Rough Guides Snapshot Scotland (includes Fort William, Glen Coe, Culloden, Inverness and Loch Ness)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QBIFi65PCocC&pg=PT25|date=12 July 2012|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-4093-6581-5|page=25}}</ref>\n\n==Flora and fauna==\n[[File:Glen affric loch affric.jpg|left|thumb|View along Glen Affric]]\nGlen Affric is listed in the Caledonian Pinewood Inventory,<ref name=\"pinewood\"/> and contains the third largest area of ancient [[Caledonian Forest|Caledonian pinewoods]] in Scotland.<ref name=\"qualities\"/> Due to the importance of this woodland it has been classified as a [[National nature reserve (Scotland)|national nature reserve]] since 2002, and holds several other conservation designations.<ref name = sitelink/> The pinewood consists predominantly of [[Scots pine]], but also includes broadleaved species such as [[birch]], [[rowan]], [[aspen]], [[willow]]s and [[alder]]. The forest floor hosts many plant species typically found in Scotland's pinewoods, including [[Goodyera repens|creeping ladies tresses]], [[Listera cordata|lesser twayblade]], [[Linnaea borealis|twinflower]], and four species of [[wintergreen]]. Many nationally rare or scarce species of [[lichen]]s grow on the trees of Glen Affric.<ref name=citation>{{cite web|url=https://apps.snh.gov.uk/sitelink-api/v1/sites/697/documents/1|title=Glen Affric SSSI Citation|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nScots pine trees first colonised the area after the last [[Last Glacial Period|Ice Age]], 10,000 to 8,000 years ago. Currently the oldest trees in the area are the gnarled \"granny\" pines that are the survivors of generations of [[tree felling|felling]]. Although felling ceased many years ago, regrowth was hampered by unnaturally high populations of sheep and deer, and in the early 1950s the Forestry Commission found that very few of the remaining pines were less than 100 years old.<ref name=nnr-ages>{{cite web |url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/nature-and-culture/the-wood-of-ages/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Wood of Ages|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=18 November 2014 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref> Initially the Commission, which was tasked with increasing the total amount of tree cover without reference to the species used, reforested the area with non-native species such as [[Sitka spruce]] and [[lodgepole pine]], as well as Scots pine from local seed stocks. Since the 1980s management priorities have changed, and non-native conifers have been felled and removed from the glen, alongside the removal of other non-native trees such as [[rhododendron]]. Some commercial forestry continues in order to maintain forest cover and to benefit local people financially, and considerable areas of non-native conifers are expected to remain in the forest over the next few decades.<ref name=LMP>{{cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/images/corporate/design-plans/irs/glen-affric/Glen-Affric-LMP-summary.pdf|title=Glen Affric Land Management Plan Vision and Summary|publisher=Forestry and Land Scotland|accessdate=3 January 2020|date= July 2019}}</ref><ref name=nnr-native/>\n\nForestry and Land Scotland (successor body to the Forestry Commission) aims to encourage regrowth of the pinewood by reducing deer numbers, thus minimising the use of fencing, which can injure [[black grouse]] and [[western capercaillie|capercaillie]] which collide with the wires.<ref name=diversity>{{cite web |url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/management/managing-for-diversity/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Managing for diversity|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=18 November 2014 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref> The long-term aim is to provide a network of forest habitats, with corridors of new forest linking existing woodland, interspersed with open areas. Management of the reserve also seeks to establish a 'treeline transition zone', in which there is a more gradual transition between woodland and mountain heath with an intermediate zone of shorter, more twisted trees and low-growing shrubs.<ref name=nnr-native>{{cite web |url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/management/return-of-the-native/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Return of the native|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=17 November 2014 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref> At the western end of the glen the National Trust for Scotland aims to encourage the growth of other tree species such as birch and rowan to complement the pinewood.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nts.org.uk/visit/places/west-affric |title=West Affric Estate|publisher=National Trust for Scotland|accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter nearly seventy years of management to encourage restoration of the area, biodiversity has improved and Glen Affric now supports birds such as [[black grouse]], [[capercaillie]], [[crested tit]] and [[Scottish crossbill]], as well as raptor species such as [[osprey]]s and [[golden eagle]]s. Glen Affric is also home to [[Scottish wildcat]]s and [[European otter|otters]]. The bogs and lochs of the glen provide a habitat for many species of dragonfly, including the rare [[Somatochlora metallica|brilliant emerald]].<ref name=\"sac\"/><ref name=\"nnr-ages\"/><ref name=citation/>\n\nIn 2019 an [[elm]] tree in Glen Affric, christened the \"Last [[Ent]] of Affric\" was named Scotland's [[Tree of the Year (United Kingdom)|Tree of the Year]] by the [[Woodland Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/blog/tree-of-the-year|title=The 'Last Ent of Affric' is Scotland's Tree of the Year 2019|publisher=Forestry and Land Scotland|date=23 October 2019|accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lady Glen Affric, nee Fanny Spencer-Churchill.jpg|thumb|right|1876\u2014Lady Glen Affric (Fanny, Baroness Tweedmouth) died in 1904 at Glen Affric Lodge on the estate where her golden retriever, Crocus, had been bred]]\nGlen Affric, also written Glenaffric,<ref name=\"tartanregister.gov.uk\">{{cite web|title=Scottish Register of Tartans \u2013 Glenaffric Fragment|url=https://www.tartanregister.gov.uk/tartanDetails.aspx?ref=1402|publisher=The Scottish Government \u2013 National Records of Scotland, H.M. General Register House|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref> was part of the lands of the [[Clan Chisholm]] and the [[Clan Fraser of Lovat]] from the 15th to the mid 19th centuries. By the early 15th century, Lord Lovat had passed the lands to his son Thomas who in turn passed it on to his son, William, who was recorded in ''[[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Landed Gentry Scotland]]'' as William Fraser, first [[Laird]] of Guisachan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Burke's Landed Gentry Scotland |url= http://www.burkespeerage.com/search_results.php?results=1|publisher=Burke\u2019s Peerage|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Highland Cowboys\">{{cite book | title=Highland Cowboys: From the Hills of Scotland to the American Wild West | publisher=Luath Press Ltd | last=Gibson|first= Rob | year=2014 | pages=Maps | isbn=9781909912960}}</ref> In 1579, Thomas Chisholm, Laird of [[River Glass, Strathglass|Strathglass]], was imprisoned for being a Catholic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Lady and St Bean's Church, Marydale \u2013 Strathglass \u2018Pestered With Popery\u2019 & Knockfin|url=http://www.stmarysbeauly.org/-history.html|publisher=Parish of St Mary, Beauly|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> By the 18th century, the [[title deeds]] of Glen Affric had been a source of feuding, with the [[Battle of Glen Affric]] taking place in 1721.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macrae |first1=A. |title=History of the Clan Macrae |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ydRrAAAAMAAJ&q=title++deeds++for++affric&dq=title++deeds++for++affric&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivjofUz-HeAhWDYysKHeyIAp0Q6AEIKDAA |publisher=Gateway Press|date= 1976 |accessdate=20 November 2018 |page=93 |quote=..... Duncan had valuable papers on his person at the time, and among them the title deeds of Affric.}}</ref>\n\nThere exists in the [[Scottish Register of Tartans]] a \"Glenaffric Fragment\" that possibly dates from the late 17th century.<ref name=\"tartanregister.gov.uk\"/>\n\n[[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley Marjoribanks, later Lord Tweedmouth]] was a rich Liberal [[Member of Parliament|MP]] who took a long lease on shooting rights over much of Glen Affric in 1846 and, by 1856, had acquired ownership of the Glen Affric Estate from \"Laird Fraser\" whose family had built the original Guisachan [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] [[manor house]] around 1755.<ref>{{cite web |title=Glen Affric  Map  Guide |url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/images/pdf/rec_pdfs/glenaffricmapguide.pdf |publisher=Forestry  Commission  Scotland |accessdate=1  September  2019 |pages=2 |quote=Lord Tweedmouth, a rich brewer and Liberal Member of  Parliament  bought   this  area  from  Laird Fraser in 1856...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Transactions of the Gaelic Society of Inverness, Volume 54 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=izEtAAAAIAAJ&q=Glen+Affric++Estate++Lord++Tweedmouth++bought&dq=Glen+Affric++Estate++Lord++Tweedmouth++bought&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDq7DZ25ndAhWJM94KHSmTA2AQ6AEIMDAC |publisher=Inverness Gaelic Society  \u2013  1987 |accessdate=1 September 2018 |quote=.. (he) first rented and then, as Lord Tweedmouth, bought Guisachan and the whole of Knockfin and Glenaffric.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=GLASGOW NATURAL HISTORY SOCIETY NEWSLETTER |url=https://www.glasgownaturalhistory.org.uk/newsletter/GNHS%20Newsletter%201%20Feb%202013.pdf |publisher=GLASGOW NATURAL HISTORY SOCIETY NEWSLETTER \u2013  February  2013 |accessdate=1 September 2018 |page=6}}</ref> The estate held over {{convert|32,000|acres|ha|order=flip}} at the time of its transference from the [[Clan Chisholm]] to Lord Tweedmouth.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Deer Stalking Grounds of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1960 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YIYcAQAAMAAJ&q=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&dq=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyw_baqankAhXXV30KHeGPC0cQ6AEILzAB|publisher=Hollis  and  Carter |quote=In 1913, Millais listed no less than eight forests in this area belonging to the Chisholms: Affric (32,000 acres), Benula (20,000 acres), Erchless (8,000 acres), Fasnakyle (25,000 acres), Glencannich (13,000 acres), Knockfin (8,000 acres), ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Glen Affric |url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/glen-affric |publisher=2019 Forestry and Land Scotland|accessdate=30  August  2019|quote=Sir Dudley Coutts Marjoribanks, the first Lord Tweedmouth, was a rich Liberal MP who took a long lease on shooting rights over much of Glen Affric in 1846, paying \u00a33,000 per year for the privilege: about \u00a3130,000 in today's money}}</ref> By the 1860s, Lord Tweedmouth, as the new laird, had much enlarged the house,<ref name=DSA>{{cite web|title=DSA Building/Design Report  \u2013 Guisachan House|url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=213774|publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects|year= 2016|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> using Scottish architect Alexander Reid who designed many buildings on Tweedmouth's vast Glen Affric Estate, including an entire village\u2014[[Tomich (village)|Tomich]]\u2014and the Glen Affric Hunting Lodge,<ref>{{cite web |title=DSA Building/Design Report  \u2013  Glen  Affric  Lodge \u2013  (1860-c1871)  Architects \u2013 A & W  Reid |url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=231251 |year= 2016 |publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> described in appearance as [[Scottish Baronial architecture|\"castle-like\"]].<ref name=Australian>{{cite news|last1=Campbell|first1=Kieran|title=Inside world's most exclusive holiday retreats  \u2013 (Glen Affric Estate)|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/inside-worlds-most-exclusive-holiday-retreats/story-e6frg6n6-1226748847087|newspaper=The Australian|date= 29 October 2014}}</ref> Tweedmouth had enjoyed shooting rights over much of Glen Affric since 1846, and, following his acquisition of the estate he initiated the first breed of [[golden retrievers]] at kennels near Guisachan House. He put the retrievers to good use at the [[deer stalking|shooting parties]] he hosted when at Glen Affric Lodge. The retrievers were sent to other estates when, for some months of the years 1870\u201371, he leased the Glen Affric Estate to Lord Grosvenor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Highlands\u2019 own little piece of Eden|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/highlands-own-little-piece-of-eden-1-2043319|newspaper=The Scotsman  |date=  8 January 2012|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Strathglass\">{{cite web|title=Strathglass|url=http://www.glenaffric.org/strathglass.html|publisher=glenaffric.org |year=2011|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Golden Retrievers ~ Research Into the First Century in the Show Ring |url=http://goldenretrieversthefirstcentury.com/Assets/book/Section%2002_Breed%20Development_%20Part%20%20A%20(3).pdf| pages=62\u20133|publisher=Tweedsmouth Publishing |first=M. N. |last=Morphet|date=2011 |isbn=|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894 [[Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth]] had inherited the Glenaffric and Guisachan estates from his father. His wife, the 2nd Baroness Tweedmouth, was born Lady Fanny Spencer-Churchill,  the daughter of the [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough|7th Duke of Marlborough]], and died at Glen Affric Lodge in 1904.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mack|first1=Ann|title=History repeats itself with the two Lady Glen Affrics|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news-feature/1245546/history-repeats-itself-with-the-two-lady-glen-affrics/|newspaper=Press and Journal  |date=  17 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> Known in the highlands as the Lady of Glenaffric and Guisachan, she was reported to be a \"lover of the [[golden retriever]] dog\".<ref name=npg>{{cite web |last1=Melhuish |first1=A. |title=Fanny Octavia Louisa (n\u00e9e Spencer-Churchill) |url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw115448/Fanny-Octavia-Louisa-ne-Spencer-Churchill-Lady-Tweedmouth-with-her-golden-retriever-Crocus#sitter |website=London National  Portrait  Gallery |publisher=A.J. (Arthur James) Melhuish |year=  1876 |accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe [[George V|Duke and Duchess of York]] are reported in ''[[The Graphic]]'', 25 September 1897 to have visited the Guisachan Estate in Strathglass, including Glen Affric Lodge. Lady Tweedmouth's nephew [[Winston Churchill]] also came to visit the estate in 1901, and amused himself learning how to drive a car in the grounds.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Strong-Boag |first1=Veronica |title= Liberal Hearts and Coronets: The Lives and Times of Ishbel Marjoribanks Gordon and John Campbell Gordon, the Aberdeens |url= https://books.google.com.au/books?id=p9fTBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=highlands+Fanny+Octavia+Louisa&source=bl&ots=ypOptNCpOH&sig=iN9CwF1KxI8LoDv2-BLjsQTmNp8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjLrfK2yKfOAhUHoZQKHWvfBesQ6AEILjAE#v=onepage&q=highlands%20Fanny%20Octavia%20Louisa&f=false |publisher= University of Toronto Press |year= 2015 |accessdate= 4 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title = Tom Weir \u2013 Men of the Trees |url= https://www.scotsmagazine.com/articles/tom-weir-men-of-the-trees/ |work= The Scots Magazine |accessdate= 26 July 2016 |year= 2016 |first= Tom |last= Weir |quote=A Glen With Connections: Fate, however, had something in store for a young man who came here to visit his aunt, wife of the second Lord Tweedmouth. Her name was Lady Fanny Spencer Churchill, and the name of her nephew who came in 1901 was Winston, who amused himself learning how to drive a car in these grounds.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title =Royal Tourism: Excursions Around Monarchy|publisher = Channel View Publications|last = Long|year = 2008|page = 76|isbn = 9781845410803|first = Phil|last2 = Palmer|first2 = Nicola J.}}</ref>\n\n[[Clan Marjoribanks|Clan Marjoribanks']] ownership ended with Edward\u2019s son, [[Dudley Churchill Marjoribanks, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley Churchill Marjoribanks]], who became 3rd Lord Tweedmouth in 1909. He and his wife had two daughters, but no male heir. For the next few years, until 1918, the estate was owned by the family of [[Newton Wallop, 6th Earl of Portsmouth]] (1856\u20131917).<ref>{{cite news |title=The Earl and Countess Portsmouth have arrived at in the heart of Glen Affric, which Lord Portsmouth  bought from Lord Tweedmouth some.... |url=https://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=lady%20portsmouth%20glen%20%20affric&from=1875&to=1949|accessdate=6 August 2019 |work=Aberdeen Press and Journal |location=Aberdeenshire, Scotland |date=7  August  1911 |quote=The Earl and Countess Portsmouth have arrived at Guisachan in the heart of Glen Affric, which Lord Portsmouth   bought  from Lord Tweedmouth some years ago. They motored from ...|via=Genes Reunited}}</ref> [[Marmaduke Furness, 1st Viscount Furness]] owned the estate throughout the 1920s and 30s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pearson |first1=H. |title=The Marrying Americans |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=DzxODwAAQBAJ&pg=PT345&dq=Glen++Affric++lord++furness&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-0N6L4PzcAhUDw7wKHWNICXwQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Glen%20%20Affric%20%20lord%20%20furness&f=false |publisher=Pickle Partners Publishing|date= 27 February 2018|isbn=9781787209572 |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> The entire property, then consisting of {{convert|22,000|acre}}, had been sold by 1936 to a Mr Hunter. It was he who resold the Glen Affric deer forest to the west and a large area of grazing land to the Forestry Commission.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last1 = Rutland|first1 = Tom|title = Breed History \u2013 The Day We Met Dileas|url = https://www.grca.org/about-the-breed/breed-history/the-day-we-met-dileas/|publisher = Golden Retriever Club of America|accessdate = 3 February 2015|last2 = Rutland|first2 = Sarah}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Golden Retriever | publisher=i5 Publishing | last=Pepper|first= Jeffrey G. | year=2012 | page=27 | isbn=9781621870340}}</ref>\n\n[[John Dickson-Poynder, 1st Baron Islington|Lady Islington]] acquired the Guisachan portion of the estate in 1939 but let the property go to ruin. In 1962 the Guisachan estate was bought by a descendant of the Frasers of Gortuleg. In 1990, this later generation laird wrote a booklet concerning his Fraser ancestors who had once owned Guisachan\u2014''Guisachan, A History by Donald Fraser''.<ref name=\"Strathglass\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=The Frasers of Guisachan |url=http://www.clanfraser.ca/guisacha.htm |publisher=Bernard Poulin & Bernard Poulin |accessdate=26 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204225647/http://www.clanfraser.ca/guisacha.htm |archivedate=4 February 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Glen Affric\">{{cite web|title=Glen Affric, In a Nutshell|url=http://www.glenaffricestate.com/|publisher=b\u00f6etic|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Friends of Guisachan|url=https://friendsofguisachan.org/main/what-is-guisachan-2/|publisher=Friends of Guisachan|accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Provost (civil)|Provost]] Robert Wotherspoon was recorded as owning Glen Affric Estate in 1951, having purchased it in 1944 and selling the \"majority of its ground to the Forestry Commission\" in 1948.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Deer Stalking Grounds of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1960 |publisher=Hollis  and  Carter |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YIYcAQAAMAAJ&q=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&dq=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyw_baqankAhXXV30KHeGPC0cQ6AEILzAB |quote=(page  120) - Glen Affric  was  one of the Chisholm's  forests until  1944 when it was purchased by  Provost Robert  Wotherspoon. Subsequently, in 1948 he had sold  the  majority  of  its  ground to the Forestry  Commission  being  granted by  the commission a lease of the sporting and grazing rights which lease was to be continued in favour of his family.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Country  Life,  Volume 175 |journal=Country Life, Limited, 1984 |date=1984 |page=160 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=rmXnAAAAMAAJ&q=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&dq=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGzJ6g3abkAhWB8nMBHQjCBV0Q6AEIPDAD |accessdate=29  August 2019 |quote=The recent sale of the 25,000-acre Glen Affric Estate, near Inverness, is by far the largest by the [Forestry] Commission. Although it never ... Simplified rules for felling a solicitor, Ian Wotherspoon, whose father  [Provost  Robert Wotherspoon]  owned it until 1951.}}</ref> His son, Iain Wotherspoon was listed as living at Glen Affric Lodge in 1958.<ref>{{cite book |title=Scottish  Birds |date=1958 |publisher=Edinburgh : Scottish Ornithologists' Club |lccn=64028211|url=https://archive.org/stream/scottishbirds4196667scot/scottishbirds4196667scot_djvu.txt |quote=....of the Forestry Commission and Mr Iain Wotherspoon, Glen Affric Lodge.}}</ref>\n\n==Current ownership==\n[[File:Affric Lodge, Glen Affric (geograph 3199291).jpg|thumb|right|Affric Lodge, on the North Affric Estate]]\n[[File:Gleann Afraig is Beinn Fhada.jpg|[[Beinn Fhada]] stands at the head of Glen Affric on the NTS West Affric Estate|thumb]]\nMost of the glen was bought by the [[Forestry Commission]] in 1951. Although the [[House of Commons]] recorded that the Commission was considering returning at least some of its Glen Affric landholdings to private ownership in the early 1980s,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates (Hansard): House of Commons Official report |date=1983 |volume=50 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=L_otAAAAYAAJ&q=glen+affric+1983+house+of+commons&dq=glen+affric+1983+house+of+commons&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitkvSFp6nkAhVSOisKHQvmBKAQ6AEINTAC |accessdate=30  August  2019 |publisher=H.M.  Stationery  Office |quote=House of Commons Official report Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons. [Mr. Archy Kirkwood] crystalised in a recent properly carried out lobby... the market to take over to such an extent that more assets are having to be sold such as Glenelg, and Glen Affric, without proper consultation? ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Country Life, Volume 175 |journal=Country Life, Limited, 1984 |date=1984 |page=160 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=rmXnAAAAMAAJ&q=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&dq=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGzJ6g3abkAhWB8nMBHQjCBV0Q6AEIPDAD |accessdate=29  August 2019 |quote=The recent sale of the 25,000-acre Glen Affric Estate, near Inverness, is by far the largest by the [Forestry] Commission.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Scientist |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YFjTMckHfuwC&pg=PA426&dq=glen+affric+sheiks&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTw8aVuKnkAhXbbSsKHb_-Cq4Q6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=glen%20affric%20sheiks&f=false |publisher=Reed  Business  Information |accessdate=30  August  2019 |page=426 |date=10 Nov 1983 |quote=..urge the Secretary of State for Scotland to prevent the Forestry Commission from returning 35,000 acres of Glen Affric to private ownership....once back in private hands, Affric could be sold off by the previous owners, the Wotherspoon family, to Arab sheikhs or Dutch speculators, who have denied the public access ...}}</ref> the majority of the glen continues to form part of Scotland's [[National Forest Estate]]. The Forestry \nCommission's successor body, [[Forestry and Land Scotland]] (FLS), is the largest single landowner in Glen Affric, holding {{convert|176|km2|sqmi}} of the lower and central parts of the glen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/managing/work-on-scotlands-national-forest-estate/conservation/habitats/woodland/glen-affric-native-woodland|title=Restoring native woodland in Glen Affric|publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland|date=2016 |accessdate= 17 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=wos>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/geo/index.htm#zoom=12&lat=57.23358&lon=-5.09878&layers=B0TT |title=Property Search |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 5 March 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe [[National Trust for Scotland]] has owned the {{cvt|37|km2|sqmi}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1177 |title=Property Page: West Affric Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 17 March 2018}}</ref> West Affric Estate, which covers the upper part of the glen,<ref name=\"wos\"/> since 1993.<ref>National Trust for Scotland 2017 Guide, p. 97.</ref>\n\nAs of 2019 the main private landowner is the North Affric Estate with {{cvt|36|km2|sqmi}} of land on the north side of Loch Affric centred on the [[Scottish baronial architecture|baronial]] Affric Lodge.<ref name=\"wos\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1431 |title=Property Page: North Affric Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 17 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Glen Affric\"/><ref name=Australian/> Since 2008 this land has been held by David Matthews, whose eldest son [[James Matthews (racing driver)|James Matthews]] is married to [[Pippa Middleton]], sister to [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]].<ref name=\"Highland Cowboys\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/|title=Pippa  could  be  Lady of  Glen|last1=Ramage|first1=I.|date=22  July  2016|work=|accessdate=31  August  2019|publisher=The Press and Journal (Inverness, Highlands and Islands)|quote=...Middleton  is marrying James Matthews, the eldest son of David  Matthews, the Laird of the glorious Glen Affric  Estate...}}</ref>\n\nThe Guisachan area of Glen Affric, which lies to the south of the main glen, is also in private hands, now forming three separate estates. Wester Guisachan Estate covers {{cvt|38|km2|sqmi}} of land to the south of Loch Affric,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1475 |title=Property Page: Wester Guisachan Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref> whilst the Hilton & Guisachan Estates lies further east and covers {{cvt|17|km2|sqmi}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1357 |title=Property Page: Hilton & Guisachan Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref> The final portion of the Guisachan Estate, which remains in the ownership of the Fraser family, consists of {{cvt|7|km2|sqmi}} at the very east of the glen including the small settlement of Tomich.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=13557 |title=Property Page: Guisachan Farm |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tomich-holidays.co.uk/guisachan-history/ |title=Guisachan History |publisher=Tomich Holidays |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs with all land in Scotland, there is a [[freedom to roam|right of responsible access]] to most of the land in the glen for pursuits such as [[hiking|walking]], [[cycling]], [[horse-riding]] and [[wild camping]]. These rights apply regardless of whether the land is in public or private ownership, provided access is exercised in accordance with the [[Scottish Outdoor Access Code]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outdooraccess-scotland.com/sites/default/files//docs/Scottish_Outdoor_Access_Code_-_Part_1_Introduction.pdf|title=Scottish Outdoor Access Code|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=2005|accessdate=16 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923165217/http://www.outdooraccess-scotland.com/sites/default/files//docs/Scottish_Outdoor_Access_Code_-_Part_1_Introduction.pdf|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Glen affric youth hostel.jpg|thumb|Glen Affric Youth Hostel]]\nGlen Affric is popular with hillwalkers, as it provides access to many [[Munro]]s and [[lists of mountains and hills in the British Isles#Corbetts|Corbetts]]. The north side of the glen forms a ridge with eight Munro summits, including the highest peak north of the [[Great Glen]], [[C\u00e0rn Eige]] {{convert|1183|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=munros>D. Bennet & R. Anderson. ''The Munros: Scottish Mountaineering Club Hillwalkers Guide'', pp. 178\u2013195. Published 2016.</ref> The three Munros at the western end of this ridge, [[Sg\u00f9rr nan Ceathreamhnan]] {{convert|1151|m|abbr=on}}, Mullach na Dheireagain {{convert|982|m|abbr=on}} and An Socach {{convert|921|m|abbr=on}}, are amongst the remotest hills in Scotland, and are often climbed from the [[Scottish Youth Hostels Association]] hostel at Alltbeithe.<ref name=\"munros\"/> The hostel is only open in the summer, and can only be reached by foot or by [[mountain bike]] via routes of between {{convert|10|and|13|km|abbr=on}} starting from lower down Glen Affric or from the [[A87 road|A87]] at [[Loch Cluanie]] or [[Morvich, Highland|Morvich]]. The dormitories are unheated and hostellers are required to bring a [[sleeping bag]], and to carry out all rubbish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syha.org.uk/where-to-stay/highlands/glen-affric.aspx |title=Glen Affric Youth Hostel |publisher=Scottish Youth Hostels Association |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref> Three miles east of the hostel is the Strawberry Cottage mountaineering hut, maintained by the An Teallach Mountaineering Club, described by [[The Scotsman]] as \"one of the best-equipped huts in the country\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle-2-15039/back-to-glen-affric-for-an-easy-lochside-walk-1-731837|title=Back to Glen Affric for an easy lochside walk|newspaper=The Scotsman|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> Glen Affric is also the starting point for routes to the summits of Munros to the south and west of the glen, although these can also be accessed from the [[Kintail]] area.<ref name=\"munros\"/> Corbetts accessible from Glen Affric include Sg\u00f9rr Gaorsaic, C\u00e0rn a' Choire Ghairbh and Aonach Shasuinn.<ref name=corbetts>R. Milne & H Brown. ''The Corbetts and Other Scottish Hills \u2013 Scottish Mountaineering Club Hillwalkers' Guide'', pp. 182\u2013185. Published 2002.</ref>\n\nThe Affric Kintail Way is a {{convert|70|km|abbr=on}} long route from [[Drumnadrochit]] on the shore of [[Loch Ness]] to Morvich in Kintail via Glen Urquhart and Glen Affric. The route is suitable for both walkers and mountain bikers, and can usually be walked in four days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://affrickintailway.com/affric-kintail-way-background.html| title=About The Affric Kintail Way |publisher=Strathglass Marketing Group |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://affrickintailway.com/affric-kintail-way-route-overview.html| title=Route Overview|publisher=Strathglass Marketing Group |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nShorter waymarked trails are provided in the lower parts of the glen, taking walkers to viewpoints and attractions such as the waterfalls at [[Plodda Falls|Plodda]] and the [[Dog Falls, Glen Affric|Dog Falls]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/images/pdf/rec_pdfs/glenaffricmapguide.pdf | title=Glen Affric Map and Guide | publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland | date=March 2017 | accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Hydro-electric scheme==\n[[Image:Benevean dam (PaulHookway.jpg| Benevean Dam|Benevean Dam on the outflow from Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin|thumb]]\nThe glen is part of the [[Affric-Beauly hydro-electric power scheme|Affric/Beauly hydroelectric scheme]], constructed by the [[North of Scotland Hydro-Electric Board]]. Loch Mullardoch, in the neighbouring [[Glen Cannich]], is dammed, and a {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} tunnel carries water to Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin, which has also been dammed. From there, another tunnel takes water to Fasnakyle power station, near [[Cannich]]. As the rivers in this scheme are important for [[Atlantic salmon]], flow in the rivers is kept above agreed levels. The dam at Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin has a [[Fish ladder|Borland fish ladder]] to allow salmon to pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish-southern.co.uk/sseinternet/assets/569CABFE-1165-4ED8-9419-CF3B5A64BC98.pdf |title=Power From the Glens |accessdate=8 March 2008 |format=PDF |publisher=[[Scottish and Southern Energy]]|page=12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018233304/http://www.scottish-southern.co.uk/sseinternet/assets/569CABFE-1165-4ED8-9419-CF3B5A64BC98.pdf |archivedate=18 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Conservation designations==\nIn addition to being a [[National nature reserve (Scotland)|national nature reserve]], Glen Affric is a [[Caledonian Forest]] Reserve,<ref name=pinewood>{{cite web|url=https://data.gov.uk/dataset/caledonian-pinewood-inventory|title=Caledonian Pinewood Inventory|publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> a [[National scenic area (Scotland)|National Scenic Area]],<ref name=nsa>{{cite web|url=https://sitelink.nature.scot/site/9126|title=Glen Affric NSA|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> and a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI).<ref name=sssi>{{cite web|url=https://sitelink.nature.scot/site/697|title=Glen Affric SSSI|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> The NNR is classified as a [[Protected_area#IUCN_Protected_Area_Management_Categories|Category II]] [[protected area]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://protectedplanet.net/glen-affric-national-nature-reserve|title=Glen Affric in United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland|publisher=Protected Planet|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> Much of the area forms part of a European Union [[Special Protection Area]] for golden eagles,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=10233|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|title=Site Details for Glen Affric to Strathconon SPA|date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref> and is also classified as an EU [[Special Area of Conservation]].<ref name=sac>{{cite web |url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=8385|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|title=Site Details for Strathglass Complex SAC|date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nGlen Affric was proposed for inclusion in a [[National parks of Scotland|national park]] by the Ramsay committee, set up following the Second World War to consider the issue of national parks in Scotland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cairngormslearningzone.co.uk/managing-the-park/the-national-park-family/history-leading-to-the-cairngorms-national-park/|title=History Leading to the Cairngorms National Park|publisher=Cairngorms National Park Authority|accessdate=15 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115185119/http://cairngormslearningzone.co.uk/managing-the-park/the-national-park-family/history-leading-to-the-cairngorms-national-park/|archive-date=15 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 2013 the Scottish Campaign for National Parks listed the area as one of seven deemed suitable for national park status,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scnp.org.uk/News/Docs/2013/Unfinished-Business-a-national-parks-strategy-for-scotland.pdf |title=Unfinished Business a national parks strategy for scotland|publisher=Scottish Campaign for National Parks|date=March 2013|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref> however as of 2019 no national park designation has occurred. In September 2016 [[Roseanna Cunningham]], the [[Cabinet Secretary for Environment, Climate Change and Land Reform]], told the [[Scottish Parliament]] that the [[Scottish Government]] had no plans to designate new national parks in Scotland and instead planned to focus on the two existing national parks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dgwgo.com/dumfries-galloway-news/scottish-government-short-sighted-over-snub-to-national-park-for-galloway/ |title=Scottish Government \"short sighted\" over snub to national park for Galloway|publisher=Dumfries and Galloway \u2013 What's Going On  |date=16 September 2016|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Glen Affric}}\n* [http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/lochness/glenaffric.shtml Glen Affric walks \u2013 free guide]\n* [https://www.nts.org.uk/visit/places/west-affric National Trust for Scotland West Affric Estate]\n* [http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/visit/glen-affric Forestry Commission Glen Affric National Nature Reserve]\n* [http://www.glenaffricestate.com/ Glen Affric Estate]\n\n{{NSAs in Scotland|state=collapsed}}\n{{National Nature Reserves of Scotland}}\n\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Inverness]]\n[[Category:National nature reserves in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Glens of Scotland|Affric]]\n[[Category:Geography of Inverness]]\n[[Category:National scenic areas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Highland (council area)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Glen Affric National Nature Reserve\n| alt_name = \n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Islands - panoramio (2).jpg\n| photo_alt = Pinewoods at Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin\n| photo_caption = Pinewoods at Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin\n| photo_width = \n| map = Scotland Highland\n| relief = 1\n| map_alt = Location within the Highland council area\n| map_caption = Location within the Highland council area\n| map_width = \n| location = [[Cannich]], [[Highland (council area)|Highland]], Scotland\n| coordinates = {{coord|57.23596|N|5.15327|W|region:GB_source:placeopedia|display=inline, title}}\n| area_km2 = 145\n| area_ref =<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=8169|title=Site Details for Glen Affric|accessdate=28 March 2018|date=5 March 2018|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage}}</ref>\n| established = 2002<ref name=scene>{{cite web|url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/nature-and-culture/setting-the-scene/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Setting the Scene|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=13 July 2016 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref>\n| designation = [[Scottish Natural Heritage]]\n| operator = [[Forestry and Land Scotland]]\n| url = [http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/visit/glen-affric Glen Affric National Nature Reserve]\n| embedded = \n}}\n'''Glen Affric''' ({{lang-gd|Gleann Afraig}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ainmean-aite.scot/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Forestry.pdf|publisher=Ainmean-\u00c0ite na h-Alba|accessdate=1 March 2019|date=2013|title=Forestry Commission 2013}}</ref> is a [[glen]] south-west of the village of [[Cannich]] in the [[Highland (council area)|Highland]] region of [[Scotland]], some {{convert|15|mi|km}} to the west of [[Loch Ness]]. The River Affric runs along its length, passing through [[Loch Affric]] and Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin. A minor public road reaches as far as the end of Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin, but beyond that point only rough tracks and footpaths continue along the glen.<ref name=sheet25>[[Ordnance Survey]] 1:50000 Landranger Sheet 25, ''Glen Carron and Glen Affric.''</ref>\n\nOften described as the most beautiful [[glen]] in Scotland, Glen Affric contains the third largest area of ancient [[Caledonian Forest|Caledonian pinewoods]] in Scotland, as well as [[loch]]s, [[moorland]] and mountains.<ref name=qualities>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.scot/sites/default/files/2017-07/Publication%202010%20-%20SNH%20Commissioned%20Report%20374%20-%20The%20Special%20Qualities%20of%20the%20National%20Scenic%20Areas.pdf|title=The special qualities of the National Scenic Areas|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=2010|accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\nThe area is a [[Caledonian Forest]] Reserve,<ref name=pinewood>{{cite web|url=https://data.gov.uk/dataset/caledonian-pinewood-inventory|title=Caledonian Pinewood Inventory|publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> a [[National scenic area (Scotland)|national scenic area]] and a [[National nature reserve (Scotland)|national nature reserve]], as well as holding several other [[protected areas of Scotland|conservation designations]].<ref name = sitelink>{{cite web| url=http://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/searchmap.jsp |title=Sitelink \u2013 Map Search |publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe forests and open landscapes of the glen, and the mountains on either side, are a popular destination for hikers, climbers and mountain bikers.<ref name=\"HumphreysReid2012\">{{cite book|first1=Rob |last1=Humphreys|first2=Donald |last2=Reid|title=The Great Glen Rough Guides Snapshot Scotland (includes Fort William, Glen Coe, Culloden, Inverness and Loch Ness)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QBIFi65PCocC&pg=PT25|date=12 July 2012|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-4093-6581-5|page=25}}</ref>\n\n==Flora and fauna==\n[[File:Glen affric loch affric.jpg|left|thumb|View along Glen Affric]]\nGlen Affric is listed in the Caledonian Pinewood Inventory,<ref name=\"pinewood\"/> and contains the third largest area of ancient [[Caledonian Forest|Caledonian pinewoods]] in Scotland.<ref name=\"qualities\"/> Due to the importance of this woodland it has been classified as a [[National nature reserve (Scotland)|national nature reserve]] since 2002, and holds several other conservation designations.<ref name = sitelink/> The pinewood consists predominantly of [[Scots pine]], but also includes broadleaved species such as [[birch]], [[rowan]], [[aspen]], [[willow]]s and [[alder]]. The forest floor hosts many plant species typically found in Scotland's pinewoods, including [[Goodyera repens|creeping ladies tresses]], [[Listera cordata|lesser twayblade]], [[Linnaea borealis|twinflower]], and four species of [[wintergreen]]. Many nationally rare or scarce species of [[lichen]]s grow on the trees of Glen Affric.<ref name=citation>{{cite web|url=https://apps.snh.gov.uk/sitelink-api/v1/sites/697/documents/1|title=Glen Affric SSSI Citation|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nScots pine trees first colonised the area after the last [[Last Glacial Period|Ice Age]], 10,000 to 8,000 years ago. Currently the oldest trees in the area are the gnarled \"granny\" pines that are the survivors of generations of [[tree felling|felling]]. Although felling ceased many years ago, regrowth was hampered by unnaturally high populations of sheep and deer, and in the early 1950s the Forestry Commission found that very few of the remaining pines were less than 100 years old.<ref name=nnr-ages>{{cite web |url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/nature-and-culture/the-wood-of-ages/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Wood of Ages|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=18 November 2014 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref> Initially the Commission, which was tasked with increasing the total amount of tree cover without reference to the species used, reforested the area with non-native species such as [[Sitka spruce]] and [[lodgepole pine]], as well as Scots pine from local seed stocks. Since the 1980s management priorities have changed, and non-native conifers have been felled and removed from the glen, alongside the removal of other non-native trees such as [[rhododendron]]. Some commercial forestry continues in order to maintain forest cover and to benefit local people financially, and considerable areas of non-native conifers are expected to remain in the forest over the next few decades.<ref name=LMP>{{cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/images/corporate/design-plans/irs/glen-affric/Glen-Affric-LMP-summary.pdf|title=Glen Affric Land Management Plan Vision and Summary|publisher=Forestry and Land Scotland|accessdate=3 January 2020|date= July 2019}}</ref><ref name=nnr-native/>\n\nForestry and Land Scotland (successor body to the Forestry Commission) aims to encourage regrowth of the pinewood by reducing deer numbers, thus minimising the use of fencing, which can injure [[black grouse]] and [[western capercaillie|capercaillie]] which collide with the wires.<ref name=diversity>{{cite web |url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/management/managing-for-diversity/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Managing for diversity|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=18 November 2014 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref> The long-term aim is to provide a network of forest habitats, with corridors of new forest linking existing woodland, interspersed with open areas. Management of the reserve also seeks to establish a 'treeline transition zone', in which there is a more gradual transition between woodland and mountain heath with an intermediate zone of shorter, more twisted trees and low-growing shrubs.<ref name=nnr-native>{{cite web |url=http://www.nnr-scotland.org.uk/glen-affric/management/return-of-the-native/|title=Glen Affric \u2013 Return of the native|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=17 November 2014 |accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref> At the western end of the glen the National Trust for Scotland aims to encourage the growth of other tree species such as birch and rowan to complement the pinewood.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nts.org.uk/visit/places/west-affric |title=West Affric Estate|publisher=National Trust for Scotland|accessdate= 6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter nearly seventy years of management to encourage restoration of the area, biodiversity has improved and Glen Affric now supports birds such as [[black grouse]], [[capercaillie]], [[crested tit]] and [[Scottish crossbill]], as well as raptor species such as [[osprey]]s and [[golden eagle]]s. Glen Affric is also home to [[Scottish wildcat]]s and [[European otter|otters]]. The bogs and lochs of the glen provide a habitat for many species of dragonfly, including the rare [[Somatochlora metallica|brilliant emerald]].<ref name=\"sac\"/><ref name=\"nnr-ages\"/><ref name=citation/>\n\nIn 2019 an [[elm]] tree in Glen Affric, christened the \"Last [[Ent]] of Affric\" was named Scotland's [[Tree of the Year (United Kingdom)|Tree of the Year]] by the [[Woodland Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/blog/tree-of-the-year|title=The 'Last Ent of Affric' is Scotland's Tree of the Year 2019|publisher=Forestry and Land Scotland|date=23 October 2019|accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lady Glen Affric, nee Fanny Spencer-Churchill.jpg|thumb|right|1876\u2014Lady Glen Affric (Fanny, Baroness Tweedmouth) died in 1904 at Glen Affric Lodge on the estate where her golden retriever, Crocus, had been bred]]\nGlen Affric, also written Glenaffric,<ref name=\"tartanregister.gov.uk\">{{cite web|title=Scottish Register of Tartans \u2013 Glenaffric Fragment|url=https://www.tartanregister.gov.uk/tartanDetails.aspx?ref=1402|publisher=The Scottish Government \u2013 National Records of Scotland, H.M. General Register House|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref> was part of the lands of the [[Clan Chisholm]] and the [[Clan Fraser of Lovat]] from the 15th to the mid 19th centuries. By the early 15th century, Lord Lovat had passed the lands to his son Thomas who in turn passed it on to his son, William, who was recorded in ''[[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Landed Gentry Scotland]]'' as William Fraser, first [[Laird]] of Guisachan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Burke's Landed Gentry Scotland |url= http://www.burkespeerage.com/search_results.php?results=1|publisher=Burke\u2019s Peerage|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Highland Cowboys\">{{cite book | title=Highland Cowboys: From the Hills of Scotland to the American Wild West | publisher=Luath Press Ltd | last=Gibson|first= Rob | year=2014 | pages=Maps | isbn=9781909912960}}</ref> In 1579, Thomas Chisholm, Laird of [[River Glass, Strathglass|Strathglass]], was imprisoned for being a Catholic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Lady and St Bean's Church, Marydale \u2013 Strathglass \u2018Pestered With Popery\u2019 & Knockfin|url=http://www.stmarysbeauly.org/-history.html|publisher=Parish of St Mary, Beauly|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> By the 18th century, the [[title deeds]] of Glen Affric had been a source of feuding, with the [[Battle of Glen Affric]] taking place in 1721.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macrae |first1=A. |title=History of the Clan Macrae |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ydRrAAAAMAAJ&q=title++deeds++for++affric&dq=title++deeds++for++affric&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivjofUz-HeAhWDYysKHeyIAp0Q6AEIKDAA |publisher=Gateway Press|date= 1976 |accessdate=20 November 2018 |page=93 |quote=..... Duncan had valuable papers on his person at the time, and among them the title deeds of Affric.}}</ref>\n\nThere exists in the [[Scottish Register of Tartans]] a \"Glenaffric Fragment\" that possibly dates from the late 17th century.<ref name=\"tartanregister.gov.uk\"/>\n\n[[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley Marjoribanks, later Lord Tweedmouth]] was a rich Liberal [[Member of Parliament|MP]] who took a long lease on shooting rights over much of Glen Affric in 1846 and, by 1856, had acquired ownership of the Glen Affric Estate from \"Laird Fraser\" whose family had built the original Guisachan [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]] [[manor house]] around 1755.<ref>{{cite web |title=Glen Affric  Map  Guide |url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/images/pdf/rec_pdfs/glenaffricmapguide.pdf |publisher=Forestry  Commission  Scotland |accessdate=1  September  2019 |pages=2 |quote=Lord Tweedmouth, a rich brewer and Liberal Member of  Parliament  bought   this  area  from  Laird Fraser in 1856...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Transactions of the Gaelic Society of Inverness, Volume 54 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=izEtAAAAIAAJ&q=Glen+Affric++Estate++Lord++Tweedmouth++bought&dq=Glen+Affric++Estate++Lord++Tweedmouth++bought&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDq7DZ25ndAhWJM94KHSmTA2AQ6AEIMDAC |publisher=Inverness Gaelic Society  \u2013  1987 |accessdate=1 September 2018 |quote=.. (he) first rented and then, as Lord Tweedmouth, bought Guisachan and the whole of Knockfin and Glenaffric.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=GLASGOW NATURAL HISTORY SOCIETY NEWSLETTER |url=https://www.glasgownaturalhistory.org.uk/newsletter/GNHS%20Newsletter%201%20Feb%202013.pdf |publisher=GLASGOW NATURAL HISTORY SOCIETY NEWSLETTER \u2013  February  2013 |accessdate=1 September 2018 |page=6}}</ref> The estate held over {{convert|32,000|acres|ha|order=flip}} at the time of its transference from the [[Clan Chisholm]] to Lord Tweedmouth.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Deer Stalking Grounds of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1960 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YIYcAQAAMAAJ&q=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&dq=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyw_baqankAhXXV30KHeGPC0cQ6AEILzAB|publisher=Hollis  and  Carter |quote=In 1913, Millais listed no less than eight forests in this area belonging to the Chisholms: Affric (32,000 acres), Benula (20,000 acres), Erchless (8,000 acres), Fasnakyle (25,000 acres), Glencannich (13,000 acres), Knockfin (8,000 acres), ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Glen Affric |url=https://forestryandland.gov.scot/visit/glen-affric |publisher=2019 Forestry and Land Scotland|accessdate=30  August  2019|quote=Sir Dudley Coutts Marjoribanks, the first Lord Tweedmouth, was a rich Liberal MP who took a long lease on shooting rights over much of Glen Affric in 1846, paying \u00a33,000 per year for the privilege: about \u00a3130,000 in today's money}}</ref> By the 1860s, Lord Tweedmouth, as the new laird, had much enlarged the house,<ref name=DSA>{{cite web|title=DSA Building/Design Report  \u2013 Guisachan House|url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=213774|publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects|year= 2016|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> using Scottish architect Alexander Reid who designed many buildings on Tweedmouth's vast Glen Affric Estate, including an entire village\u2014[[Tomich (village)|Tomich]]\u2014and the Glen Affric Hunting Lodge,<ref>{{cite web |title=DSA Building/Design Report  \u2013  Glen  Affric  Lodge \u2013  (1860-c1871)  Architects \u2013 A & W  Reid |url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=231251 |year= 2016 |publisher=Dictionary of Scottish Architects |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> described in appearance as [[Scottish Baronial architecture|\"castle-like\"]].<ref name=Australian>{{cite news|last1=Campbell|first1=Kieran|title=Inside world's most exclusive holiday retreats  \u2013 (Glen Affric Estate)|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/inside-worlds-most-exclusive-holiday-retreats/story-e6frg6n6-1226748847087|newspaper=The Australian|date= 29 October 2014}}</ref> Tweedmouth had enjoyed shooting rights over much of Glen Affric since 1846, and, following his acquisition of the estate he initiated the first breed of [[golden retrievers]] at kennels near Guisachan House. He put the retrievers to good use at the [[deer stalking|shooting parties]] he hosted when at Glen Affric Lodge. The retrievers were sent to other estates when, for some months of the years 1870\u201371, he leased the Glen Affric Estate to Lord Grosvenor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Highlands\u2019 own little piece of Eden|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/highlands-own-little-piece-of-eden-1-2043319|newspaper=The Scotsman  |date=  8 January 2012|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Strathglass\">{{cite web|title=Strathglass|url=http://www.glenaffric.org/strathglass.html|publisher=glenaffric.org |year=2011|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Golden Retrievers ~ Research Into the First Century in the Show Ring |url=http://goldenretrieversthefirstcentury.com/Assets/book/Section%2002_Breed%20Development_%20Part%20%20A%20(3).pdf| pages=62\u20133|publisher=Tweedsmouth Publishing |first=M. N. |last=Morphet|date=2011 |isbn=|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894 [[Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth]] had inherited the Glenaffric and Guisachan estates from his father. His wife, the 2nd Baroness Tweedmouth, was born Lady Fanny Spencer-Churchill,  the daughter of the [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough|7th Duke of Marlborough]], and died at Glen Affric Lodge in 1904.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mack|first1=Ann|title=History repeats itself with the two Lady Glen Affrics|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news-feature/1245546/history-repeats-itself-with-the-two-lady-glen-affrics/|newspaper=Press and Journal  |date=  17 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> Known in the highlands as the Lady of Glenaffric and Guisachan, she was reported to be a \"lover of the [[golden retriever]] dog\".<ref name=npg>{{cite web |last1=Melhuish |first1=A. |title=Fanny Octavia Louisa (n\u00e9e Spencer-Churchill) |url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw115448/Fanny-Octavia-Louisa-ne-Spencer-Churchill-Lady-Tweedmouth-with-her-golden-retriever-Crocus#sitter |website=London National  Portrait  Gallery |publisher=A.J. (Arthur James) Melhuish |year=  1876 |accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe [[George V|Duke and Duchess of York]] are reported in ''[[The Graphic]]'', 25 September 1897 to have visited the Guisachan Estate in Strathglass, including Glen Affric Lodge. Lady Tweedmouth's nephew [[Winston Churchill]] also came to visit the estate in 1901, and amused himself learning how to drive a car in the grounds.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Strong-Boag |first1=Veronica |title= Liberal Hearts and Coronets: The Lives and Times of Ishbel Marjoribanks Gordon and John Campbell Gordon, the Aberdeens |url= https://books.google.com.au/books?id=p9fTBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=highlands+Fanny+Octavia+Louisa&source=bl&ots=ypOptNCpOH&sig=iN9CwF1KxI8LoDv2-BLjsQTmNp8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjLrfK2yKfOAhUHoZQKHWvfBesQ6AEILjAE#v=onepage&q=highlands%20Fanny%20Octavia%20Louisa&f=false |publisher= University of Toronto Press |year= 2015 |accessdate= 4 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title = Tom Weir \u2013 Men of the Trees |url= https://www.scotsmagazine.com/articles/tom-weir-men-of-the-trees/ |work= The Scots Magazine |accessdate= 26 July 2016 |year= 2016 |first= Tom |last= Weir |quote=A Glen With Connections: Fate, however, had something in store for a young man who came here to visit his aunt, wife of the second Lord Tweedmouth. Her name was Lady Fanny Spencer Churchill, and the name of her nephew who came in 1901 was Winston, who amused himself learning how to drive a car in these grounds.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title =Royal Tourism: Excursions Around Monarchy|publisher = Channel View Publications|last = Long|year = 2008|page = 76|isbn = 9781845410803|first = Phil|last2 = Palmer|first2 = Nicola J.}}</ref>\n\n[[Clan Marjoribanks|Clan Marjoribanks']] ownership ended with Edward\u2019s son, [[Dudley Churchill Marjoribanks, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley Churchill Marjoribanks]], who became 3rd Lord Tweedmouth in 1909. He and his wife had two daughters, but no male heir. For the next few years, until 1918, the estate was owned by the family of [[Newton Wallop, 6th Earl of Portsmouth]] (1856\u20131917).<ref>{{cite news |title=The Earl and Countess Portsmouth have arrived at in the heart of Glen Affric, which Lord Portsmouth  bought from Lord Tweedmouth some.... |url=https://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=lady%20portsmouth%20glen%20%20affric&from=1875&to=1949|accessdate=6 August 2019 |work=Aberdeen Press and Journal |location=Aberdeenshire, Scotland |date=7  August  1911 |quote=The Earl and Countess Portsmouth have arrived at Guisachan in the heart of Glen Affric, which Lord Portsmouth   bought  from Lord Tweedmouth some years ago. They motored from ...|via=Genes Reunited}}</ref> [[Marmaduke Furness, 1st Viscount Furness]] owned the estate throughout the 1920s and 30s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pearson |first1=H. |title=The Marrying Americans |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=DzxODwAAQBAJ&pg=PT345&dq=Glen++Affric++lord++furness&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-0N6L4PzcAhUDw7wKHWNICXwQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Glen%20%20Affric%20%20lord%20%20furness&f=false |publisher=Pickle Partners Publishing|date= 27 February 2018|isbn=9781787209572 |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> The entire property, then consisting of {{convert|22,000|acre}}, had been sold by 1936 to a Mr Hunter. It was he who resold the Glen Affric deer forest to the west and a large area of grazing land to the Forestry Commission.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last1 = Rutland|first1 = Tom|title = Breed History \u2013 The Day We Met Dileas|url = https://www.grca.org/about-the-breed/breed-history/the-day-we-met-dileas/|publisher = Golden Retriever Club of America|accessdate = 3 February 2015|last2 = Rutland|first2 = Sarah}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Golden Retriever | publisher=i5 Publishing | last=Pepper|first= Jeffrey G. | year=2012 | page=27 | isbn=9781621870340}}</ref>\n\n[[John Dickson-Poynder, 1st Baron Islington|Lady Islington]] acquired the Guisachan portion of the estate in 1939 but let the property go to ruin. In 1962 the Guisachan estate was bought by a descendant of the Frasers of Gortuleg. In 1990, this later generation laird wrote a booklet concerning his Fraser ancestors who had once owned Guisachan\u2014''Guisachan, A History by Donald Fraser''.<ref name=\"Strathglass\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=The Frasers of Guisachan |url=http://www.clanfraser.ca/guisacha.htm |publisher=Bernard Poulin & Bernard Poulin |accessdate=26 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204225647/http://www.clanfraser.ca/guisacha.htm |archivedate=4 February 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Glen Affric\">{{cite web|title=Glen Affric, In a Nutshell|url=http://www.glenaffricestate.com/|publisher=b\u00f6etic|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Friends of Guisachan|url=https://friendsofguisachan.org/main/what-is-guisachan-2/|publisher=Friends of Guisachan|accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Provost (civil)|Provost]] Robert Wotherspoon was recorded as owning Glen Affric Estate in 1951, having purchased it in 1944 and selling the \"majority of its ground to the Forestry Commission\" in 1948.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Deer Stalking Grounds of Great Britain and Ireland |date=1960 |publisher=Hollis  and  Carter |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YIYcAQAAMAAJ&q=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&dq=Provost++Robert++wotherspoon++glen++affric&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiyw_baqankAhXXV30KHeGPC0cQ6AEILzAB |quote=(page  120) - Glen Affric  was  one of the Chisholm's  forests until  1944 when it was purchased by  Provost Robert  Wotherspoon. Subsequently, in 1948 he had sold  the  majority  of  its  ground to the Forestry  Commission  being  granted by  the commission a lease of the sporting and grazing rights which lease was to be continued in favour of his family.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Country  Life,  Volume 175 |journal=Country Life, Limited, 1984 |date=1984 |page=160 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=rmXnAAAAMAAJ&q=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&dq=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGzJ6g3abkAhWB8nMBHQjCBV0Q6AEIPDAD |accessdate=29  August 2019 |quote=The recent sale of the 25,000-acre Glen Affric Estate, near Inverness, is by far the largest by the [Forestry] Commission. Although it never ... Simplified rules for felling a solicitor, Ian Wotherspoon, whose father  [Provost  Robert Wotherspoon]  owned it until 1951.}}</ref> His son, Iain Wotherspoon was listed as living at Glen Affric Lodge in 1958.<ref>{{cite book |title=Scottish  Birds |date=1958 |publisher=Edinburgh : Scottish Ornithologists' Club |lccn=64028211|url=https://archive.org/stream/scottishbirds4196667scot/scottishbirds4196667scot_djvu.txt |quote=....of the Forestry Commission and Mr Iain Wotherspoon, Glen Affric Lodge.}}</ref>\n\n==Current ownership==\n[[File:Affric Lodge, Glen Affric (geograph 3199291).jpg|thumb|right|Affric Lodge, on the North Affric Estate]]\n[[File:Gleann Afraig is Beinn Fhada.jpg|[[Beinn Fhada]] stands at the head of Glen Affric on the NTS West Affric Estate|thumb]]\nMost of the glen was bought by the [[Forestry Commission]] in 1951. Although the [[House of Commons]] recorded that the Commission was considering returning at least some of its Glen Affric landholdings to private ownership in the early 1980s,<ref>{{cite journal |title=Parliamentary Debates (Hansard): House of Commons Official report |date=1983 |volume=50 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=L_otAAAAYAAJ&q=glen+affric+1983+house+of+commons&dq=glen+affric+1983+house+of+commons&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitkvSFp6nkAhVSOisKHQvmBKAQ6AEINTAC |accessdate=30  August  2019 |publisher=H.M.  Stationary  Office |quote=House of Commons Official report Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons. [Mr. Archy Kirkwood] crystalised in a recent properly carried out lobby... the market to take over to such an extent that more assets are having to be sold such as Glenelg, and Glen Affric, without proper consultation? ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Country Life, Volume 175 |journal=Country Life, Limited, 1984 |date=1984 |page=160 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=rmXnAAAAMAAJ&q=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&dq=glen+affric+estate+wotherspoon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGzJ6g3abkAhWB8nMBHQjCBV0Q6AEIPDAD |accessdate=29  August 2019 |quote=The recent sale of the 25,000-acre Glen Affric Estate, near Inverness, is by far the largest by the [Forestry] Commission.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Scientist |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=YFjTMckHfuwC&pg=PA426&dq=glen+affric+sheiks&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTw8aVuKnkAhXbbSsKHb_-Cq4Q6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=glen%20affric%20sheiks&f=false |publisher=Reed  Business  Information |accessdate=30  August  2019 |page=426 |date=10 Nov 1983 |quote=..urge the Secretary of State for Scotland to prevent the Forestry Commission from returning 35,000 acres of Glen Affric to private ownership....once back in private hands, Affric could be sold off by the previous owners, the Wotherspoon family, to Arab sheikhs or Dutch speculators, who have denied the public access ...}}</ref> the majority of the glen continues to form part of Scotland's [[National Forest Estate]]. The Forestry \nCommission's successor body, [[Forestry and Land Scotland]] (FLS), is the largest single landowner in Glen Affric, holding {{convert|176|km2|sqmi}} of the lower and central parts of the glen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/managing/work-on-scotlands-national-forest-estate/conservation/habitats/woodland/glen-affric-native-woodland|title=Restoring native woodland in Glen Affric|publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland|date=2016 |accessdate= 17 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=wos>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/geo/index.htm#zoom=12&lat=57.23358&lon=-5.09878&layers=B0TT |title=Property Search |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 5 March 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe [[National Trust for Scotland]] has owned the {{cvt|37|km2|sqmi}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1177 |title=Property Page: West Affric Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 17 March 2018}}</ref> West Affric Estate, which covers the upper part of the glen,<ref name=\"wos\"/> since 1993.<ref>National Trust for Scotland 2017 Guide, p. 97.</ref>\n\nAs of 2019 the main private landowner is the North Affric Estate with {{cvt|36|km2|sqmi}} of land on the north side of Loch Affric centred on the [[Scottish baronial architecture|baronial]] Affric Lodge.<ref name=\"wos\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1431 |title=Property Page: North Affric Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 17 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Glen Affric\"/><ref name=Australian/> Since 2008 this land has been held by David Matthews, whose eldest son [[James Matthews (racing driver)|James Matthews]] is married to [[Pippa Middleton]], sister to [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]].<ref name=\"Highland Cowboys\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/|title=Pippa  could  be  Lady of  Glen|last1=Ramage|first1=I.|date=22  July  2016|work=|accessdate=31  August  2019|publisher=The Press and Journal (Inverness, Highlands and Islands)|quote=...Middleton  is marrying James Matthews, the eldest son of David  Matthews, the Laird of the glorious Glen Affric  Estate...}}</ref>\n\nThe Guisachan area of Glen Affric, which lies to the south of the main glen, is also in private hands, now forming three separate estates. Wester Guisachan Estate covers {{cvt|38|km2|sqmi}} of land to the south of Loch Affric,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1475 |title=Property Page: Wester Guisachan Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref> whilst the Hilton & Guisachan Estates lies further east and covers {{cvt|17|km2|sqmi}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=1357 |title=Property Page: Hilton & Guisachan Estate |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref> The final portion of the Guisachan Estate, which remains in the ownership of the Fraser family, consists of {{cvt|7|km2|sqmi}} at the very east of the glen including the small settlement of Tomich.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoownsscotland.org.uk/property.php?p=13557 |title=Property Page: Guisachan Farm |publisher=Who Owns Scotland |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tomich-holidays.co.uk/guisachan-history/ |title=Guisachan History |publisher=Tomich Holidays |accessdate= 18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs with all land in Scotland, there is a [[freedom to roam|right of responsible access]] to most of the land in the glen for pursuits such as [[hiking|walking]], [[cycling]], [[horse-riding]] and [[wild camping]]. These rights apply regardless of whether the land is in public or private ownership, provided access is exercised in accordance with the [[Scottish Outdoor Access Code]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outdooraccess-scotland.com/sites/default/files//docs/Scottish_Outdoor_Access_Code_-_Part_1_Introduction.pdf|title=Scottish Outdoor Access Code|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|date=2005|accessdate=16 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923165217/http://www.outdooraccess-scotland.com/sites/default/files//docs/Scottish_Outdoor_Access_Code_-_Part_1_Introduction.pdf|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Glen affric youth hostel.jpg|thumb|Glen Affric Youth Hostel]]\nGlen Affric is popular with hillwalkers, as it provides access to many [[Munro]]s and [[lists of mountains and hills in the British Isles#Corbetts|Corbetts]]. The north side of the glen forms a ridge with eight Munro summits, including the highest peak north of the [[Great Glen]], [[C\u00e0rn Eige]] {{convert|1183|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=munros>D. Bennet & R. Anderson. ''The Munros: Scottish Mountaineering Club Hillwalkers Guide'', pp. 178\u2013195. Published 2016.</ref> The three Munros at the western end of this ridge, [[Sg\u00f9rr nan Ceathreamhnan]] {{convert|1151|m|abbr=on}}, Mullach na Dheireagain {{convert|982|m|abbr=on}} and An Socach {{convert|921|m|abbr=on}}, are amongst the remotest hills in Scotland, and are often climbed from the [[Scottish Youth Hostels Association]] hostel at Alltbeithe.<ref name=\"munros\"/> The hostel is only open in the summer, and can only be reached by foot or by [[mountain bike]] via routes of between {{convert|10|and|13|km|abbr=on}} starting from lower down Glen Affric or from the [[A87 road|A87]] at [[Loch Cluanie]] or [[Morvich, Highland|Morvich]]. The dormitories are unheated and hostellers are required to bring a [[sleeping bag]], and to carry out all rubbish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syha.org.uk/where-to-stay/highlands/glen-affric.aspx |title=Glen Affric Youth Hostel |publisher=Scottish Youth Hostels Association |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref> Three miles east of the hostel is the Strawberry Cottage mountaineering hut, maintained by the An Teallach Mountaineering Club, described by [[The Scotsman]] as \"one of the best-equipped huts in the country\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle-2-15039/back-to-glen-affric-for-an-easy-lochside-walk-1-731837|title=Back to Glen Affric for an easy lochside walk|newspaper=The Scotsman|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> Glen Affric is also the starting point for routes to the summits of Munros to the south and west of the glen, although these can also be accessed from the [[Kintail]] area.<ref name=\"munros\"/> Corbetts accessible from Glen Affric include Sg\u00f9rr Gaorsaic, C\u00e0rn a' Choire Ghairbh and Aonach Shasuinn.<ref name=corbetts>R. Milne & H Brown. ''The Corbetts and Other Scottish Hills \u2013 Scottish Mountaineering Club Hillwalkers' Guide'', pp. 182\u2013185. Published 2002.</ref>\n\nThe Affric Kintail Way is a {{convert|70|km|abbr=on}} long route from [[Drumnadrochit]] on the shore of [[Loch Ness]] to Morvich in Kintail via Glen Urquhart and Glen Affric. The route is suitable for both walkers and mountain bikers, and can usually be walked in four days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://affrickintailway.com/affric-kintail-way-background.html| title=About The Affric Kintail Way |publisher=Strathglass Marketing Group |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://affrickintailway.com/affric-kintail-way-route-overview.html| title=Route Overview|publisher=Strathglass Marketing Group |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nShorter waymarked trails are provided in the lower parts of the glen, taking walkers to viewpoints and attractions such as the waterfalls at [[Plodda Falls|Plodda]] and the [[Dog Falls, Glen Affric|Dog Falls]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/images/pdf/rec_pdfs/glenaffricmapguide.pdf | title=Glen Affric Map and Guide | publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland | date=March 2017 | accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Hydro-electric scheme==\n[[Image:Benevean dam (PaulHookway.jpg| Benevean Dam|Benevean Dam on the outflow from Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin|thumb]]\nThe glen is part of the [[Affric-Beauly hydro-electric power scheme|Affric/Beauly hydroelectric scheme]], constructed by the [[North of Scotland Hydro-Electric Board]]. Loch Mullardoch, in the neighbouring [[Glen Cannich]], is dammed, and a {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} tunnel carries water to Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin, which has also been dammed. From there, another tunnel takes water to Fasnakyle power station, near [[Cannich]]. As the rivers in this scheme are important for [[Atlantic salmon]], flow in the rivers is kept above agreed levels. The dam at Loch Beinn a' Mheadhoin has a [[Fish ladder|Borland fish ladder]] to allow salmon to pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottish-southern.co.uk/sseinternet/assets/569CABFE-1165-4ED8-9419-CF3B5A64BC98.pdf |title=Power From the Glens |accessdate=8 March 2008 |format=PDF |publisher=[[Scottish and Southern Energy]]|page=12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018233304/http://www.scottish-southern.co.uk/sseinternet/assets/569CABFE-1165-4ED8-9419-CF3B5A64BC98.pdf |archivedate=18 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Conservation designations==\nIn addition to being a [[National nature reserve (Scotland)|national nature reserve]], Glen Affric is a [[Caledonian Forest]] Reserve,<ref name=pinewood>{{cite web|url=https://data.gov.uk/dataset/caledonian-pinewood-inventory|title=Caledonian Pinewood Inventory|publisher=Forestry Commission Scotland|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> a [[National scenic area (Scotland)|National Scenic Area]],<ref name=nsa>{{cite web|url=https://sitelink.nature.scot/site/9126|title=Glen Affric NSA|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> and a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI).<ref name=sssi>{{cite web|url=https://sitelink.nature.scot/site/697|title=Glen Affric SSSI|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> The NNR is classified as a [[Protected_area#IUCN_Protected_Area_Management_Categories|Category II]] [[protected area]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://protectedplanet.net/glen-affric-national-nature-reserve|title=Glen Affric in United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland|publisher=Protected Planet|accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref> Much of the area forms part of a European Union [[Special Protection Area]] for golden eagles,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=10233|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|title=Site Details for Glen Affric to Strathconon SPA|date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref> and is also classified as an EU [[Special Area of Conservation]].<ref name=sac>{{cite web |url=https://gateway.snh.gov.uk/sitelink/siteinfo.jsp?pa_code=8385|publisher=Scottish Natural Heritage|title=Site Details for Strathglass Complex SAC|date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nGlen Affric was proposed for inclusion in a [[National parks of Scotland|national park]] by the Ramsay committee, set up following the Second World War to consider the issue of national parks in Scotland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cairngormslearningzone.co.uk/managing-the-park/the-national-park-family/history-leading-to-the-cairngorms-national-park/|title=History Leading to the Cairngorms National Park|publisher=Cairngorms National Park Authority|accessdate=15 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115185119/http://cairngormslearningzone.co.uk/managing-the-park/the-national-park-family/history-leading-to-the-cairngorms-national-park/|archive-date=15 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 2013 the Scottish Campaign for National Parks listed the area as one of seven deemed suitable for national park status,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scnp.org.uk/News/Docs/2013/Unfinished-Business-a-national-parks-strategy-for-scotland.pdf |title=Unfinished Business a national parks strategy for scotland|publisher=Scottish Campaign for National Parks|date=March 2013|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref> however as of 2019 no national park designation has occurred. In September 2016 [[Roseanna Cunningham]], the [[Cabinet Secretary for Environment, Climate Change and Land Reform]], told the [[Scottish Parliament]] that the [[Scottish Government]] had no plans to designate new national parks in Scotland and instead planned to focus on the two existing national parks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dgwgo.com/dumfries-galloway-news/scottish-government-short-sighted-over-snub-to-national-park-for-galloway/ |title=Scottish Government \"short sighted\" over snub to national park for Galloway|publisher=Dumfries and Galloway \u2013 What's Going On  |date=16 September 2016|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Glen Affric}}\n* [http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/lochness/glenaffric.shtml Glen Affric walks \u2013 free guide]\n* [https://www.nts.org.uk/visit/places/west-affric National Trust for Scotland West Affric Estate]\n* [http://scotland.forestry.gov.uk/visit/glen-affric Forestry Commission Glen Affric National Nature Reserve]\n* [http://www.glenaffricestate.com/ Glen Affric Estate]\n\n{{NSAs in Scotland|state=collapsed}}\n{{National Nature Reserves of Scotland}}\n\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Inverness]]\n[[Category:National nature reserves in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Glens of Scotland|Affric]]\n[[Category:Geography of Inverness]]\n[[Category:National scenic areas of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Highland (council area)]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent ownership:Typo fixing, replaced: Stationary  Office \u2192 Stationery  Office", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glen_Affric"}
